      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":10,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. Let your body absorb the work from last week. Gentle foot mobility or calf stretching is fine if your physio has cleared it.\"},{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"20-minute easy run at 5:58/km — the slower end of your easy range. This is your physiotherapist-cleared pace. If any foot discomfort arises, shift to a run/walk pattern immediately. No heroics today.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Your tendons and fascia recover more slowly than your cardiovascular system — this gap is doing real work for you.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"notes\":\"Optional low-impact cross-training if you feel good — pool walking, swimming, or cycling. Keep it easy and stop if you feel any foot pull. Completely optional; rest is equally valid.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Three days between your Tuesday run and your Thursday-to-Saturday block gives the plantar fascia time to settle.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"20-minute easy run at 5:58/km. Check in with your foot in the first 5 minutes. If it feels off, walk the remainder — that still counts as a successful session. Consistency over distance right now.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"Your Saturday long run — 20 minutes easy at 5:58/km. Same rules apply: run/walk if needed. The goal this week is simply completing three sessions without foot aggravation. That is the win.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome back, James. This first week is built around one core principle: consistency without aggravation. Your physio has cleared you for 20-minute easy runs, and that ceiling is your guide — not a limitation to push past, but a smart boundary that protects the progress you've already made. Three runs of up to 20 minutes each puts you around 10 km for the week, which is a meaningful and appropriate step up from your recent 3–3.4 km single-run weeks. All running is at 5:58/km — the easy end of your Daniels-derived easy range — because your plantar fascia responds better to lower impact stress at this stage. No speed work, no tempo, no intervals. Those are coming, but not yet. The optional cross-training on Wednesday is there if you want to move without adding foot load. If your foot talks to you at any point this week, listen to it — drop to a walk, cut the run short, and that is still a good day. The goal of Week 1 is simple: three sessions, no setbacks, build the habit back.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
